Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with
a large drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon}, half the @garlic powder{1%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest later),
@salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until browned and tender,
~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, slice @tomato{1} into ½-inch-thick rounds; season with salt and pepper.

Halve @brioche buns{2}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @creamy shawarma sauce{2%ounce}, @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon},
and remaining garlic powder.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add tomato slices and
cook until browned, ~{2-4%minutes} per side. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, @shawarma spice blend{1%tablespoon},
and @chicken stock concentrate{1}. Form into two patties (four patties for 4 servings),
each slightly wider than a burger bun; season with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for tomato over medium-high heat. Add patties and
cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.

While patties cook, toast buns until golden brown.

Once potato wedges are done roasting, divide between plates.

Spread cut sides of buns with a thin layer of shawarma mayo. Fill buns with cooked
tomato slices, patties, and as much @hot sauce{2%teaspoon} as you like.

Serve burgers alongside potato wedges, with remaining shawarma mayo on the side
for dipping.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.